    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-claim",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model correctly identifies worst-case hemolysis operating condition for FDA generic centrifugal blood pump",
      "description": "The CFD hemolysis model, applying the modified power-law damage accumulation formulation (Giersiepen-Wurzinger coefficients), correctly rank-orders all five flow-speed operating points by relative hemolysis index and identifies the 2 L/min, 3500 RPM condition as the worst-case scenario. The model prediction is consistent with published experimental trends for the FDA benchmark pump geometry and supports the regulatory submission claim that RH < 1 across the intended operating envelope for the CPB device.",
      "scope": "FDA generic centrifugal blood pump; 5 operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM); MRL 2; Class II device; CPB surgical context",
      "purpose": "Establish model credibility sufficient to support a 510(k) submission argument that CFD-predicted hemolysis is conservative relative to the predicate device across the full operating envelope"
    }
  ],
